From: Nadeem Abdul Hamid <nadeem@acm.org>
To: Robby Findler <robby@eecs.northwestern.edu>
Cc: bugs@racket-lang.org, nobody@racket-lang.org,
        bug-notification@racket-lang.org
Subject: Re: [racket-bug] all/12466: Request a bitmap/file function in 2htdp/image
Date: Thu, 29 Dec 2011 18:17:18 -0500

 So, I have a simple n-body simulation lab exercise written in BSL that
 loads data regarding planets/stars from a text file in the current
 directory using the batch-io functions; part of the information in the
 text file is the name of an image file for each body - the image files
 are also in the current directory. So I needed a way to load a bitmap
 from file based on information parsed from the text file - hence
 bitmap/file. Now if a student were to make an executable distribution
 of their program, then it won't even include the text file in the
 distribution archive, to say nothing of the images, so it's obviously
 not going to work. But that doesn't mean the functions in the batch-io
 library are useless, and I think the same holds for the bitmap/file
 function. I do think that a note or warning in the docs for both
 libraries would be sufficient - warning that executables created from
 programs that use these types of functions may not be correctly
 generated because the requisite external resources won't be properly
 bundled (or, to get them to work properly, the resources need to be
 manually copied to the same directory in which the executable is
 placed).
 
 Alternatively, in full Racket, is there a way to specify names of
 external resources that should be included when creating a
 distribution archive? If so, maybe a simple interface to that facility
 could be provided in the student languages or one of the teachpacks,
 so if you really want to enable users of *SL to be able to create
 executables that load files or images, it will work properly. But
 perhaps this might be too complex of a feature to provide in the
 teachpacks.
 
 
 On Thu, Dec 29, 2011 at 12:42 PM, Robby Findler
 <robby@eecs.northwestern.edu> wrote:
 > Yes, putting them into a list or something would work. It is the lack
 > of convenience that I'm kind of shooting for, since I can't actually
 > support the operation properly.
 >
 > Perhaps that is wrong-headed of me. I could also just put a big
 > warning in the docs. Opinions?
 >
 > Robby
